Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build
Object: A database containing 13 relational tables and lists.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$traits
Object: A table containing measurements of traits.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$traits
Object: Includes information that must be recorded at the Measurement or Observation level.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$contexts
Object: A table containing observations of contextual characteristics associated with information in `traits`. Cross referencing between the two dataframes is possible using combinations of the variables `dataset_id`, `link_id`, and `link_vals`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$locations
Object: A table containing observations of location/site characteristics associated with information in `traits`. Cross referencing between the two dataframes is possible using combinations of the variables `dataset_id`, `location_name`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$methods
Object: A table containing details on methods with which data were collected, including time frame and source. Cross referencing with the `traits` table is possible using combinations of the variables `dataset_id`, `trait_name`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$taxa
Object: A table containing details on taxa associated with information in `traits`. Whenever possible, this information is sourced from curated taxon lists that include identifiers for each taxon. The information compiled in this table is released under a CC-BY3 license. Cross referencing between the two dataframes is possible using combinations of the variable `taxon_name`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$sources
Object: A list containing citation details for all database sources.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$definitions
Object: A list containing trait concept descriptions used to build the database.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$contributors
Object: A table of people contributing to each study.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/traits.build$taxonomic_updates
Object: A table of all taxonomic changes implemented in the construction of AusTraits. Changes are determined by comparing the originally submitted taxon name against the taxonomic names listed in the taxonomic reference files, best placed in a subfolder in the `config` folder . Cross referencing with the `traits` table is possible using combinations of the variables `dataset_id` and `taxon_name`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/dataset
Object: 13 relational tables and lists containing all data about a dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation
Object: An Observation is a collection of measurements made at a single point in time. In traits.build it is the subset of rows within the traits data that are made on the same entity and share the same observation_id.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation
Object: An observation is an assertion that an entity (e.g., biological organisms, geographic locations, or environmental features, among others) was observed by an observer. An observation primarily serves to group a set of measurements together into a single "observation event". Observations are often made within a broader context. The context of an observation is given by other observations, implying that an observed entity (and specifically each corresponding measurement) contextualizes another observed entity (and its corresponding measurements). For example, an observation associated with a location may serve as context for an observation associated with an organism. In this case, the observed characteristic values of the location (such as humidity) are assumed constant for the corresponding measurements of the organism.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_from_dataset
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations that comprise a dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_from_source
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations for a single published or unpublished source.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_of_taxon
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations on a single taxon within a single dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_of_taxon
Object: An observation collection is a container for a set of observations.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_at_location
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations at a single location.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_of_population
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations on a single population.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observations_of_individual
Object: Observation collection encompassing all observations on a single individual.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_treatment_context_property
Object: Observation where entity is a context indicating experimental manipulations that might affect the trait values measured on an individual, population or species-level entities.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_treatment_context_property
Object: Examples include growing temperature, growing CO2 concentrations, and nutrient amendments.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_plot_context_property
Object: Observation where entity is a category of context indicating variation across plots at a single location might affect the trait values measured on individual or population-level entities.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_entity_context_property
Object: Observation where entity is a category of context indicating repeat observations have been made on an individual, population or species-level entity across time which might affect the entity's measured trait values.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_temporal_context_property
Object: Observation where entity is a category of context indicating repeat observations have been made on a plot, which might affect the trait values measured on individual or population-level entities.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_of_temporal_context_property
Object: Examples of temporal contexts are `sampling season`, `sampling time of day`, and sequential `observation numbers` without any linked categorical description.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement
Object: A measurement is an assertion that a characteristic of an entity had a particular value with respect to an observation event.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/trait_measurement
Object: A measurement made on a trait.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_of_location_property
Object: A measurement made on a location property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_of_treatment_context_property
Object: A measurement made on a treatment context property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_of_plot_context_property
Object: A measurement made on a plot context property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_of_entity_context_property
Object: A measurement made on an entity context property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_of_temporal_context_property
Object: A measurement made on a temporal context property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/entity
Object: An entity is an object (e.g., a tree, a community, an ecological process). Entities constitute the foci of observations, i.e., every observation is of exactly one entity.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/population
Object: A collection of organisms, all of the same species, that live in the same place.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/location
Object: A spatial region or named place.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/context
Object: The situation within which a trait measurement is made, which can help explain the measured trait value.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/plot
Object: A subdivision of a location, designated because some properties differ across plots within a location, which might cause differences in measured trait values between plots.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/treatment
Object: An experimental manipulation that subjects different individuals or populations to different conditions, which can lead to differences in measured trait values across treatments.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/temporal_context
Object: A situation or process that varies across time and might cause the measured trait values of individuals or populations to change across time.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/method_context
Object: A compment of a trait measurement protocol that is changed between individual trait measurements and might cause the measured trait values of individuals or populations to change.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/dataset_id
Object: Primary identifier for each study contributed to AusTraits, most often these are scientific papers, books, or online resources. By default this should be the name of the first author and year of publication, e.g. `Falster_2005`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon_name
Object: Scientific name of the taxon on which traits were sampled, without authorship. When possible, this is the currently accepted (botanical) or valid (zoological) scientific name, but might also be a higher taxonomic level.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/observation_id
Object: A unique integral identifier for the observation, where an observation is all measurements made on an individual at a single point in time. It is important for joining traits coming from the same `observation_id`. Within each dataset, observation_id's are unique combinations of `taxon_name`, `population_id`, `individual_id`, and `temporal_context_id`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/trait_name
Object: Name of the trait sampled. Allowable values specified in the table `definitions`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/value
Object: The measured value of a trait.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/unit
Object: Units of the sampled trait value after aligning with AusTraits standards.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/entity_type
Object: A categorical variable specifying the entity corresponding to the trait values recorded.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/value_type
Object: A categorical variable describing the statistical nature of the trait value recorded.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/basis_of_value
Object: A categorical variable describing how the trait value was obtained.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/replicates
Object: Number of replicate measurements that comprise a recorded trait measurement. A numeric value (or range) is ideal and appropriate if the value type is a `mean`, `median`, `min` or Â `max`. For these value types, if replication is unknown the entry should be `unknown`. If the value type is `raw_value` the replicate value should be 1. If the trait is categorical or the value indicates a measurement for an entire species (or other taxon) replicate value should be `.na`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/basis_of_record
Object: A categorical variable specifying from which kind of specimen traits were recorded.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/life_stage
Object: A field to indicate the life stage or age class of the entity measured. Standard values are `adult`, `sapling`, `seedling` and `juvenile`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/population_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for a population, where a population is defined as individuals growing in the same location (location_id /location_name) and plot (plot_context_id, a context category) and being subjected to the same treatment (treatment_context_id, a context category).

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/individual_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for an individual, with individuals numbered sequentially within each dataset by taxon by population grouping. Most often each row of data represents an individual, but in some datasets trait data collected on a single individual is presented across multiple rows of data, such as if the same trait is measured using different methods or the same individual is measured repeatedly across time.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/repeat_measurements_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for repeat measurements of a trait that comprise a single observation, such as a response curve.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_id
Object: For datasets that are compilations, an identifier for the original data source.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/location_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for a location, with locations numbered sequentially within a dataset. The identifier links to specific information in the location table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/treatment_context_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for a treatment, where a treatment is any experimental manipulation to an organism's growing/living conditions. The identifier links to specific information in the context table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/plot_context_id
Object: A unique integer identifier for a plot, where a plot is a distinct collection of organisms within a single geographic location, such as plants growing on different aspects or blocks in an experiment. The identifier links to specific information in the context table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/entity_context_id
Object: A unique integer identifier indicating specific contextual properties of an individual, possibly including the individual's sex or caste (for social insects).

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/temporal_context_id
Object: A unique integer identifier assigned where repeat observations are made on the same individual (or population, or taxon) across time. The identifier links to specific information in the context table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/method_context_id
Object: A unique integer identifier indicating a trait is measured multiple times on the same entity, with different methods used for each entry. This field is only used if a single trait is measured using multiple methods within the same dataset. The identifier links to specific information in the context table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/collection_date
Object: Date sample was taken, in the format `yyyy-mm-dd`, `yyyy-mm` or `yyyy`, depending on the resoluton specified. Alternatively an overall range for the study can be indicating, with the starting and ending sample date sepatated by a `/`, as in 2010-10/2011-03

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/measurement_remarks
Object: Brief comments or notes accompanying the trait measurement.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/method_id
Object: A unique integer identifier to distinguish between multiple sets of methods used to measure a single trait within the same dataset. The identifier links to specific information in the methods table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/original_name
Object: Name given to taxon in the original data supplied by the authors.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/locations$location_name
Object: The location name used by the data contributor or a generic location name designated by AusTraits when one is not provided.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/locations$location_property
Object: The location characteristic being recorded. The name should include units of measurement, e.g. `MAT (C)`. Ideally we have at least the following variables for each location, `longitude (deg)`, `latitude (deg)`, `description`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/locations$value
Object: The measured value of a location property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/latitude
Object: The geographic latitude (in decimal degrees, using the spatial reference system given in geodeticDatum) of the geographic center of a Location. Positive values are north of the Equator, negative values are south of it. Legal values lie between -90 and 90, inclusive.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/longitude
Object: The geographic longitude (in decimal degrees, using the spatial reference system given in dwc:geodeticDatum) of the geographic center of a dcterms:Location. Positive values are east of the Greenwich Meridian, negative values are west of it. Legal values lie between -180 and 180, inclusive.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/elevation
Object: The elevation above mean sea level in meters.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/context_property
Object: The contextual characteristic being recorded. If applicable, name should include units of measurement, e.g. `CO2 concentration (ppm)`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/treatment_context_property
Object: A context characteristic indicating stratified treatments that might affect the trait values measured on an individual or population-level entity.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/plot_context_property
Object: A context characteristic indicating stratified variation within a location that might affect the trait values measured on an individual or population-level entity.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/entity_context_property
Object: A context characteristic indicating stratified variation across individuals or populations might affect the trait values measured.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/temporal_context_property
Object: A context characteristic indicating stratified variation across time might affect the trait values measured.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/method_context_property
Object: A context characteristic indicating stratified variation in the protocol used to measure traits might affect the trait values measured.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contexts$category
Object: The category of context property, with options being `plot`, `treatment`, `individual_context`, `temporal` and `method`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contexts$value
Object: The measured value of a context property.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contexts$description
Object: Description of a specific context property value.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contexts$link_id
Object: Variable indicating which identifier column in the traits table contains the specified `link_vals`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contexts$link_vals
Object: Unique integer identifiers that link between identifier columns in the `traits` table and the contextual properties/values in the `contexts` table.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/methods$methods
Object: A textual description of the methods used to collect the trait data. Whenever available, methods are taken near-verbatim from the referenced source. Methods can include descriptions such as 'measured on botanical collections', 'data from the literature', or a detailed description of the field or lab methods used to collect the data.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/methods$description
Object: A 1-2 sentence description of the purpose of the study.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/sampling_strategy
Object: When available, this information is lifted verbatim from a published manuscript. For preserved specimens, this field ideally indicates which records were 'sampled' to measure a specific trait.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_primary_key
Object: Citation key for the primary source in `sources`. The key is typically formatted as `Surname_year`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_primary_citation
Object: Citation for the primary source. This detail is generated from the primary source in the metadata.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_secondary_key
Object: Citation key for the secondary source in `sources`.  The key is typically formatted as `Surname_year`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_secondary_citation
Object: Citations for the secondary source. This detail is generated from the secondary source in the metadata.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_original_dataset_key
Object: Citation key for the original dataset_id in sources, for compilations.  The key is typically formatted as `Surname_year`.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/source_original_dataset_citation
Object: Citations for the original dataset_id in sources, for compilationse. This detail is generated from the original source in the metadata.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/contributor
Object: A person contributing to a dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/assistants
Object: People who played a more minor role in data collection for the study.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/dataset_curators
Object: Database team member(s) who contacted the data collectors and added the study to the database repository.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/data_collector
Object: Person contributing to a dataset as a data collector.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/last_name
Object: Last name of the data collector.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/given_name
Object: Given names of the data collector.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/ORCID
Object: ORCID (Open Researcher and Contributor ID) for the data collector, if available.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/additional_role
Object: Any additional roles the data collector had in the study, a field most frequently used to identify which data contributor is the contact person for the dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/original_name
Object: Name given to taxon in the original data supplied by the authors.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxonomic_dataset
Object: Name of the taxonomy (tree) that contains this concept. ie. APC, AusMoss etc.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon_rank
Object: The taxonomic rank of the most specific name in the scientific name.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon_rank
Object: This is to clarify cases where information is not given on a species level.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/trinomial
Object: The infraspecific taxon name match for an original name. This column is assigned `na` for taxon name that are at a broader taxonomic_resolution.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/binomial
Object: The species-level taxon name match for an original name. This column is assigned `na` for taxon name that are at a broader taxonomic_resolution.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/genus
Object: Genus of the taxon without authorship.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon_distribution
Object: Known distribution of the taxon, by Australian state.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/establishment_means
Object: Statement about whether an organism or organisms have been introduced to a given place and time through the direct or indirect activity of modern humans.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxonomic_status
Object: The status of the use of the scientificName as a label for the taxon in regard to the 'accepted (or valid) taxonomy'. The assigned taxonomic status must be linked to a specific taxonomic reference that defines the concept.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/scientific_name
Object: The full scientific name, with authorship and date information if known.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon_id
Object: An identifier for the set of taxon information (data associated with the taxon class). May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to the data set. Must be resolvable within this dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/scientific_name_id
Object: An identifier for the set of taxon information (data associated with the taxon class). May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to the data set. Must be resolvable within this dataset.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxon
Object: A group of organisms assumed to form a homogeneous unit with regard to associated trait measurements.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/aligned_name
Object: The taxon name without authorship after implementing automated syntax standardisation and spelling changes as well as manually encoded syntax alignments for this taxon in the metadata file for the corresponding `dataset_id`. This name has not yet been matched to the currently accepted (botanical) or valid (zoological) taxon name in cases where there are taxonomic synonyms, isonyms, orthographic variants, etc.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/taxonomic_resolution
Object: The rank of the most specific taxon name (or scientific name) to which a submitted orignal name resolves.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/trait
Object: A collection of trait values pertaining to a distinct characteristic of a specific part of an organism (cell, tissue, organ, or whole organism).

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/trait_concept_URI
Object: Unique identifier of the trait according to a public ontology, or a user-provided thesaurus of traits.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/label
Object: A concise English label for the trait.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/description
Object: A short description, generally ranging from 1-3 sentences that clearly indicates the traitâs scope.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/comments
Object: Additional notes about the scope of the trait or acceptable methods.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/allowed_values_max
Object: An upper boundary for accepted numerical values.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/allowed_values_min
Object: A lower boundary for accepted numerical values.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/units
Object: The preferred units for the trait, conforming to the Unified Code for Units of Measure (UCUM). There are often two entries for units, one that is a string and the second which links to a units of measurement axiom.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/allowed_values_levels
Object: Allowed trait values for a categorical trait, including a brief description of the value.

Subject: https://w3id.org/traits.build/type
Object: Type of trait, specifying if traits are categorical, numeric, or ordinal.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-characteristics.owl#Identifier>
Object: Provides an identifying sequence of characters to refer to an entity within a context. An Identifier can be unique within a local context or a global context.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Characteristic>
Object: A characteristic represents a property of an entity that can be measured (e.g., height, length, or color). A characteristic of an entity is observed through a measurement, which further asserts a value of the characteristic for the entity. A characteristic type (e.g., "height") can be associated with many different entities, whereas an individual characteristic (a particular occurrence of the "height" characteristic) is associated to exactly one entity.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Standard>
Object: A standard defines a reference for comparing or naming entities via a measurement. A standard can be defined intentionally (e.g., as in the case of units) or extensionally (by listing the values of the standard, e.g., for color this might be red, blue, yellow, etc).

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Entity>
Object: An entity is an object (e.g., a tree, a community, an ecological process). Entities constitute the foci of observations, i.e., every observation is of exactly one entity.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Observation>
Object: An observation is an assertion that an entity (e.g., biological organisms, geographic locations, or environmental features, among others) was observed by an observer. An observation primarily serves to group a set of measurements together into a single "observation event". Observations are often made within a broader context. The context of an observation is given by other observations, implying that an observed entity (and specifically each corresponding measurement) contextualizes another observed entity (and its corresponding measurements). For example, an observation associated with a location may serve as context for an observation associated with an organism. In this case, the observed characteristic values of the location (such as humidity) are assumed constant for the corresponding measurements of the organism.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#ObservationCollection>
Object: An observation collection is a container for a set of observations.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Protocol>
Object: A protocol is a procedure for generating or processing data.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Measurement>
Object: A measurement is an assertion that a characteristic of an entity had a particular value with respect to an observation event. A measurement is comprised of a characteristic, a value, a measurement standard, and a protocol. Measurements can also have precision as well as a description of the methods used. Measurements can encapsulate characteristics that were recorded, but not necessarily measured in a physical sense. For example, the name of a location and a taxon can be captured through measurements.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#Unit>
Object: A unit is a standard quantification for physical measurements. A unit is either a base unit, a composite unit, or a derived unit.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#BaseCharacteristicQualifier>
Object: A base qualifier denotes a simple, atomic qualifier such as average, minimum, and maximum.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#MeasurementType>
Object: A MeasurementType describes the type of a Measurement in which the Measurement would follow the associated Protocol to record the value of the associated Characteristic of the associated Entity using the associated Standard. Any of these associated properties may be omitted, in which case the MeasurementType is only constrained by the provided associations. A MeasurementType is a hypothetical construct, in that it is not associated with a particular instance of a Measurement.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#MeasuredValue>
Object: A measurement value is a quantitative or qualitative result of a measurement. Measurement values can contain a coded representation of the result, e.g., as a number or string.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#characteristicFor>
Object: The characteristicFor property gives the entity of the characteristic.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#ofEntity>
Object: The ofEntity property gives the observed entity of an observation.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#hasValue>
Object: The hasValue property gives the value of the measurement.

Subject: <http://ecoinformatics.org/oboe/oboe.1.2/oboe-core.owl#hasContext>
Object: The hasContext property asserts that one observation serves as the context for another observation. In a hasContext property the domain is the observation being contextualized and the range is the context. Context defines a semantic relationship between two entities that is a fundamental aspect of the observations, but not necessarily of the entities themselves. For example, most measurements are accomplished in a spatio-temporal framework that might be valuable context. The assertions made by contextual observations are assumed of the contextualized observations. Context is a transitive relationship.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/Taxon>
Object: A group of organisms (sensu http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100026) considered by taxonomists to form a homogeneous unit.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/taxonID>
Object: An identifier for the set of dwc:Taxon information. May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to the data set.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/establishmentMeans>
Object: Statement about whether an organism or organisms have been introduced to a given place and time through the direct or indirect activity of modern humans.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/family>
Object: The full scientific name of the family in which the taxon is classified.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/genus>
Object: The full scientific name of the genus in which the dwc:Taxon is classified.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/infraspecificEpithet>
Object: The name of the lowest or terminal infraspecific epithet of the dwc:scientificName, excluding any rank designation.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/specificEpithet>
Object: The name of the first or species epithet of the dwc:scientificName.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/taxonRank>
Object: The taxonomic rank of the most specific name in the dwc:scientificName.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/nomenclaturalCode>
Object: The nomenclatural code (or codes in the case of an ambiregnal name) under which the dwc:scientificName is constructed.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/taxonomicStatus>
Object: The status of the use of the dwc:scientificName as a label for a taxon. Requires taxonomic opinion to define the scope of a dwc:Taxon. Rules of priority then are used to define the taxonomic status of the nomenclature contained in that scope, combined with the experts opinion. It must be linked to a specific taxonomic reference that defines the concept.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/scientificName>
Object: The full scientific name, with authorship and date information if known. When forming part of a dwc:Identification, this should be the name in lowest level taxonomic rank that can be determined. This term should not contain identification qualifications, which should instead be supplied in the dwc:identificationQualifier term.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/taxonID>
Object: An identifier for the set of dwc:Taxon information. May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to the data set.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/scientificNameID>
Object: An identifier for the nomenclatural (not taxonomic) details of a scientific name.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/Taxon>
Object: A group of organisms (sensu http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100026) considered by taxonomists to form a homogeneous unit.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/identificationQualifier>
Object: A brief phrase or a standard term ("cf.", "aff.") to express the determiner's doubts about the dwc:Identification.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/samplingProtocol>
Object: The names of, references to, or descriptions of the methods or protocols used during a dwc:Event.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/samplingProtocol>
Object: Recommended best practice is describe a dwc:Event with no more than one sampling protocol. In the case of a summary Event with multiple protocols, in which a specific protocol can not be attributed to specific dwc:Occurrences, the recommended best practice is to separate the values in a list with space vertical bar space ( | ). This term has an equivalent in the dwciri: namespace that allows only an IRI as a value, whereas this term allows for any string literal value.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/datasetID>
Object: An identifier for the set of data. May be a global unique identifier or an identifier specific to a collection or institution.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/decimalLatitude>
Object: The geographic latitude (in decimal degrees, using the spatial reference system given in dwc:geodeticDatum) of the geographic center of a dcterms:Location. Positive values are north of the Equator, negative values are south of it. Legal values lie between -90 and 90, inclusive.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/decimalLongitude>
Object: The geographic longitude (in decimal degrees, using the spatial reference system given in dwc:geodeticDatum) of the geographic center of a dcterms:Location. Positive values are east of the Greenwich Meridian, negative values are west of it. Legal values lie between -180 and 180, inclusive.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/verbatimElevation>
Object: The original description of the elevation (altitude, usually above sea level) of the Location.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/measurementValue>
Object: The value of the measurement, fact, characteristic, or assertion.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/measurementValue>
Object: This term has an equivalent in the dwciri: namespace that allows only an IRI as a value, whereas this term allows for any string literal value.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/acceptedNameUsage>
Object: The full name, with authorship and date information if known, of the currently valid (zoological) or accepted (botanical) dwc:Taxon.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/acceptedNameUsage>
Object: The full scientific name, with authorship and date information if known, of the accepted (botanical) or valid (zoological) name in cases where the provided dwc:scientificName is considered by the reference indicated in the dwc:accordingTo property, or of the content provider, to be a synonym or misapplied name. When applied to a dwc:Organism or dwc:Occurrence, this term should be used in cases where a content provider regards the provided dwc:scientificName to be inconsistent with the taxonomic perspective of the content provider. For example, there are many discrepancies within specimen collections and observation datasets between the recorded name (e.g., the most recent identification from an expert who examined a specimen, or a field identification for an observed dwc:Organism), and the name asserted by the content provider to be taxonomically accepted.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/lifeStage>
Object: The age class or life stage of the dwc:Organism(s) at the time the dwc:Occurrence was recorded.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/lifeStage>
Object: Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary. This term has an equivalent in the dwciri: namespace that allows only an IRI as a value, whereas this term allows for any string literal value.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/basisOfRecord>
Object: The specific nature of the data record.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/basisOfRecord>
Object: Recommended best practice is to use a controlled vocabulary such as the set of local names of the identifiers for classes in Darwin Core.

Subject: <http://rs.tdwg.org/dwc/terms/attributes/organizedInClass>
Object: Used to organize properties within classes for easier human understanding.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#scopeNote>
Object: A note that helps to clarify the meaning and/or the use of a concept.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#inScheme>
Object: Relates a resource (for example a concept) to a concept scheme in which it is included.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#broader>
Object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more general in meaning.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#narrower>
Object: Relates a concept to a concept that is more specific in meaning.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#prefLabel>
Object: The preferred lexical label for a resource, in a given language.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#altLabel>
Object: An alternative lexical label for a resource.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#closeMatch>
Object: skos:closeMatch is used to link two concepts that are sufficiently similar that they can be used interchangeably in some information retrieval applications. In order to avoid the possibility of compound errors when combining mappings across more than two concept schemes, skos:closeMatch is not declared to be a transitive property.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2004/02/skos/core#relatedMatch>
Object: skos:relatedMatch is used to state an associative mapping link between two conceptual resources in different concept schemes.

Subject: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#Datatype>
Object: rdfs:Datatype is the class of datatypes. All instances of rdfs:Datatype correspond to the RDF model of a datatype described in the RDF Concepts specification [RDF12-CONCEPTS]. rdfs:Datatype is both an instance of and a subclass of rdfs:Class. Each instance of rdfs:Datatype is a subclass of rdfs:Literal.

Subject: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/description>
Object: Description may include but is not limited to: an abstract, a table of contents, a graphical representation, or a free-text account of the resource.

Subject: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/contributor>
Object: An entity responsible for making contributions to the resource.

Subject: <http://purl.org/dc/terms/location>
Object: A spatial region or named place.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000673>
Object: Has unique identifier is an inverse functional relation between an entity and an identifier that uniquely identifies it.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000674>
Object: Is unique identifier for is a relation between an identifier and an entity that it uniquely identifies.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000671>
Object: A relation between an entity and an identifier.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000672>
Object: A relation between an identifier and an entity.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000255>
Object: Has annotation is a relation between an entity and some textual anntotation.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000254>
Object: Is annotation of is a relation between some textual entity and the entity that it annotates.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000223>
Object: Has unique identifier is an inverse functional relation between an entity and an identifier that uniquely identifies it.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000224>
Object: Is property of is a relation betweena quality, capability or role and the entity that it and it alone bears.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_001096>
Object: Is specialization of is a relation between a more specific instance (in terms of spatial/temporal localization & other attributres) than the other.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000001>
Object: A is related to B iff there is some relation between A and B.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000642>
Object: Is base for is a relation between a quality and the realizable entity that it is the basis for.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000641>
Object: Has basis is a relation between a realizable entity and the quality that forms the basis for it.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000628>
Object: Refers to is a relation between one entity and the entity that it makes reference to.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000754>
Object: A database table is a set of named columns with zero or more rows composed of cells that contain column values and is part of a database.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000750>
Object: A database is a set of tables.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_001187>
Object: A database row is a row that is part of a database table.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000757>
Object: A database collumn is a column in a database table.

Subject: <http://semanticscience.org/resource/SIO_000602>
Object: A computational entity is an information content entity operated on using some computational system.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/traitDescription>
Object: A short, unambiguous definition of the trait as used in the specific study context; may refer to a method of measurement; may copy the description of a public trait ontology;

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/traitDescription>
Object: The definition should make use of terms provided by existing public ontologies, e.g. 'the mass (PATO:mass), either fresh or dried, of a fruit (PO:fruit)'

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/minAllowedValue>
Object: A lower boundary for accepted numerical values.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/minAllowedValue>
Object: May be used for eliminating invalid data. This boundary may constrain a range of values of meaningful orders of magnitude.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/maxAllowedValue>
Object: An upper boundary for accepted numerical values.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/maxAllowedValue>
Object: May be used for eliminating invalid data. This boundary may constrain a range of values of meaningful orders of magnitude, or constrain entries to positive values.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/valueType>
Object: Type of trait values. Possible entries are 'numeric', 'integer', 'categorical', 'ordinal', 'logical', or 'character'.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/valueType>
Object: Numerical values represent measurements of length, volumes, ratios, rates or timespans. Integer values apply to count data (e.g.Â eggs per clutch). Binary data (encoded as 0 or 1) or logical data (coded as TRUE or FALSE) may apply to qualitative traits such as specific behavior during mating (e.g.Â are territories defended) or specialization to a given habitat (e.g.Â species restricted to relicts of primeval forests). Categorical traits should define a constrained set of factor levels, such as sex differences in wing morphology (both sexes winged, both sexes unwinged, only males winged, only females winged) or unconstrained entries such as color. Ordinal categorical traits may be better encoded as integer values, e.g.Â a logical sequence as in the case of life stages or hibernation stages, or habitat preference traits such as horizontal stratum use.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/identifier>
Object: A unique identifier for the trait; globally unique or dataset-specific

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/identifier>
Object: Identifiers are ideally globally unique and stable URIs which link to the source of the trait description in a public ontology or thesaurus of traits;

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/trait>
Object: Trait names should be unique but intuitively comprehensible. Additional specifications such as unit of measurement can be included in the name. Several words are separated by â_â.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/expectedUnit>
Object: The unit expected for measurement entries.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/expectedUnit>
Object: Only applies to numerical traits. Should be given in SI units.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/factorLevels>
Object: A comma separated list of terms comprising the constrained vocabulary for categorical traits or ordinal binary traits.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/factorLevels>
Object: Ordinal traits may be encoded with numerically indexed factor levels; e.g. 1_egg, 2_larvae, 3_pupae, 4_adult; the field traitDescription should define the factor levels;

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/comments>
Object: Details and Examples for clarification of the trait definition.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/comments>
Object: Can contain definition of trait levels or requirements for standardized conditions.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/Occurrence>
Object: An extension that contains information on the level of individual specimens, such as date and location, or method of sampling and preservation, or physiological specifications of the phenotype, such as sex, life stage or age.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/MeasurementOrFact>
Object: An extension that contains information at the level of single measurements or reported values, such as the original literature from where the value is cited, the method of measurement or statistical method used for aggregation.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/Taxon>
Object: An extension provides further terms for specifying the taxonomic resolution of the observation.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/individualCount>
Object: If measurement is an aggregate measure of multiple individuals or specimens, report number of specimens as count, i.e. integer number. Defaults to 1

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/datasetDescription>
Object: Description may include but is not limited to: an abstract, a table of contents, a graphical representation, or a free-text account of the resource.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/traitID>
Object: Unique identifier of the trait according to a public ontology, or a user-provided thesaurus of traits.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/eventDate>
Object: The date-time or interval during which an Event occurred. For occurrences, this is the date-time when the event was recorded. Not suitable for a time in a geological context. Recommended best practice is to use an encoding scheme, such as ISO 8601:2004(E). For lower precision, use year, month and day field instead.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/traitValue>
Object: Standardized measured value or factor level for this species trait. Numerical values must use the correct unit. Factor levels must be compliant with the thesaurus of traits.

Subject: <http://terminologies.gfbio.org/terms/ETS/traitUnit>
Object: The units associated with the measurementValue. The expected standard unit for this trait as defined in the traitlist/ thesaurus.

Subject: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/PCO_0000001>
Object: A collection of organisms, all of the same species, that live in the same place.

Subject: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/OBI_0100026>
Object: A material entity that is an individual living system, such as animal, plant, bacteria or virus, that is capable of replicating or reproducing, growth and maintenance in the right environment. An organism may be unicellular or made up, like humans, of many billions of cells divided into specialized tissues and organs.

Subject: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0020017>
Object: An identifier that is typically a part of a person's name which has been passed, according to law or custom, from one or both parents to their children.

Subject: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0020016>
Object: A personal name that specifies and differentiates between members of a group of individuals, especially in a family, all of whose members usually share the same family name (surname). A given name is purposefully given, usually by a child's parents at or near birth, in contrast to an inherited one such as a family name.

Subject: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/IAO_0000708>
Object: A centrally registered identifier that is issued by ORCID (https://orcid.org/) and used to persistantly identify oneself as a human researcher or contributor.

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/hasContributorAffiliation>
Object: The organizational or institutional affiliation of the contributor.

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/ContributorRole>
Object: The role of the contributor in bringing the described dataset into existence.

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/ContactPerson>
Object: Person with knowledge of how to access, troubleshoot, or otherwise field issues related to the resource

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/DataCurator>
Object: Person tasked with reviewing, enhancing, cleaning, or standardizing metadata and the associated data submitted for storage, use, and maintenance within a data centre or repository

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/DataCollector>
Object: Person/institution responsible for finding, gathering/collecting data under the guidelines of the author(s) or Principal Investigator (PI)

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/RelatedPerson>
Object: A person without a specifically defined role in the development of the resource, but who is someone the author wishes to recognize.

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/RightsHolder>
Object: Person or institution owning or managing property rights, including intellectual property rights over the resource.

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/Cites>
Object: indicates that A includes B in a citation

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/IsCitedBy>
Object: indicates that B includes A in a citation

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/Compiles>
Object: indicates B is the result of a compile or creation event using A

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/IsCompiledBy>
Object: indicates B is used to compile or create A

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/HasMetadata>
Object: indicates resource A has additional metadata B

Subject: <http://vocab.fairdatacollective.org/gdmt/IsMetadataFor>
Object: indicates additional metadata A for a resource B
